snippet.textDisplay:
I felt like a slight misdemeanor had been made in delegating the artists in this song; it was beautiful, but the composition felt hurried, this time. 

Since they're both beautiful singers, who'll smash it in varied genres; rather than merging them together, Coke studio could have made solo pieces which featured the full extent of their potentials.

The male artist had such a melodious tenor in him, which makes one nostalgic when hearing him, 

While the female has a haunting voice, I've heard her in bhul shomoy before, and for some reason, that song makes me extremely melancholic, but I keep coming back to hear it.

I too agree with the people here who mentioned of proper pronunciation, which was quite an issue, since one can hear it,

The best way I can conclude is, these two are contemporary, albeit very distinct artists; 

The way you guys created the modern iteration of "ghum ghum ghum" and delegated Fairooz Nazifa to sing it the way she did, the piece felt contemporary, but extremely tailored, apt. Like it was well thought out, and you found the perfect artist to sing that piece.

But this felt hurried, and although they both complimented the other, one could still hear the dissonance, which is created when two extremely polarised styles are merged together.

They both deserve separate pieces, which showcase them separately, that would feel like justice, since now, many are flailing to see one above the other.
